article.description: Sam Cassell scored 27 points and Ray Allen added 21 as the Milwaukee Bucks beat Detroit 89-82 Sunday, snapping the Pistons' franchise-record eight game road winning streak.
article.headline: Pistons finally lose on road, Bucks a game up

images.name: Ham_Darvin 020224 inline
images.caption: Detroit's Jerry Stackhouse, right, tries to get away from Milwaukee's Darvin Ham. Stackhouse was harassed into just 8-for-27 shooting.

article.linkText: Bucks atop Central after beating rival Pistons
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Now that they've got the Central Division lead, the Milwaukee Bucks don't plan on relinquishing it easily. Sam Cassell scored 27 points, and Ray Allen added 21 as the Bucks beat Detroit 89-82 Sunday and snapped the Pistons' franchise-record seven-game road winning streak. Milwaukee moved into sole possession of first place in the division at 32-22, one game ahead of the Pistons. "This was a big win for us," Cassell said. "We were playing for first place in the Central. Now we've got control of first place like we should have. But, we have to continue to play good basketball. If we keep playing hard, good things will happen to this ballclub." Jerry Stackhouse led the Pistons with 19 points on 8-of-27 shooting. Chucky Atkins added 17 points, and Ben Wallace added his first career triple-double with 10 points, 17 rebounds and 10 blocks. "You've got to give them credit," Wallace said. "They didn't surrender. It's a tough loss, but we've had tough losses before. We've bounced back from worse games than this. Everybody's got their head high." The Bucks led 71-63 after three quarters, but Detroit closed to 74-71 on a jumper by Corliss Williamson with 5:38 remaining. Allen countered by scoring Milwaukee's next seven points to make it 81-74 with 3:33 left. Jon Barry converted a four-point play as Detroit closed to 84-80. Stackhouse made two free throws to keep Detroit within four at 86-82 with 1:14 left. After Barry missed a 3-pointer from the left corner with 29 seconds left, Cassell hit two free throws with 16.9 seconds remaining to make it 88-82. The Bucks had just one field goal over the final 5:20, scoring 10 of their last 12 points from the line. Detroit, which had won eight of 10, shot 31-for-85 (36.5 percent) in the game. "It just came down to being able to make some shots and get a few more stops against a very potent offensive team," Detroit coach Rick Carlisle said. "We held them to 42.1 percent, which isn't bad, but they still had enough to beat us." Milwaukee seized control with a 12-point run in the first half, scoring the final six points of the first quarter and the first six of the second to open a 30-19 lead. Milwaukee led 47-38 at the half and maintained at least a seven-point lead throughout the third. "I like the way we played in the first half," Bucks coach George Karl said. "We didn't get loose when we had the lead and we played solid defensively."

Game notes
The Bucks had seven 3-pointers, ending a streak of four straight games with at least 10. ... Milwaukee is 25-2 when tied or leading after three periods. ... Detroit's 14 blocks were the most this season by a Bucks' opponent. ... Wallace's 10 blocks tied Philadelphia's Dikembe Mutombo for the league high this season.
